"""Write lessons 671-720."""
import json

lessons = []

# I'll build lessons one at a time
def add(id, kanji, kana, meaning, tags, lesson):
    lessons.append({"id": id, "kanji": kanji, "kana": kana, "meaning": meaning, "tags": tags, "lesson": lesson})

add(671, "\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4", "\u3059\u307d\u30fc\u3064", "sport", ["noun", "loan word"],
    '<p>Borrowed from English "sports" but stripped down to a singular concept. In Japanese, <span class="jp">\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4</span> is always singular in feel \u2014 you don\u2019t say <span class="jp wrong">\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4\u30ba</span>. It covers everything from baseball to table tennis to marathon running, with no separate word for "athletics" needed.</p><p>What\u2019s worth knowing: <span class="jp">\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4</span> is a \u3059\u308b-noun. <span class="jp-example">\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4\u3059\u308b</span> <span class="gloss">(to do sports, to play sports)</span> sounds natural in Japanese, even though "to do a sport" sounds slightly off in English. And the compound <span class="jp-example">\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4\u30de\u30f3</span> doesn\u2019t mean "athlete" the way you\u2019d expect \u2014 it means someone who\u2019s sporty, who has good sportsmanship. The actual word for a competitive athlete is <span class="jp">\u9078\u624b</span> <span class="gloss">(\u305b\u3093\u3057\u3085)</span>.</p>')

add(672, "\u30c1\u30e3\u30f3\u30b9", "\u3061\u3083\u3093\u3059", "chance, opportunity", ["noun", "loan word"],
    '<p>From English "chance," but Japanese <span class="jp">\u30c1\u30e3\u30f3\u30b9</span> leans heavily toward the positive sense \u2014 an opportunity, an opening. You wouldn\u2019t normally use it for random probability the way English does ("there\u2019s a chance of rain"). For that, you\u2019d say <span class="jp">\u53ef\u80fd\u6027</span> <span class="gloss">(\u304b\u306e\u3046\u305b\u3044)</span> or just <span class="jp">\u304b\u3082\u3057\u308c\u306a\u3044</span>.</p><p><span class="jp">\u30c1\u30e3\u30f3\u30b9</span> lives in the same space as <span class="jp">\u6a5f\u4f1a</span> <span class="gloss">(\u304d\u304b\u3044)</span>, the native word for "opportunity." The difference is register and feel. <span class="jp">\u6a5f\u4f1a</span> is formal, measured \u2014 something you\u2019d see in a business email. <span class="jp">\u30c1\u30e3\u30f3\u30b9</span> is energetic, almost exciting \u2014 <span class="jp-example">\u4eca\u304c\u30c1\u30e3\u30f3\u30b9\u3060\uff01</span> <span class="gloss">(now\u2019s our chance!)</span>. It carries a sense of urgency that <span class="jp">\u6a5f\u4f1a</span> doesn\u2019t.</p>')

add(673, "\u30af\u30ea\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0", "\u304f\u308a\u30fc\u306b\u3093\u3050", "dry cleaning", ["noun", "loan word"],
    '<p>This is one of those loanwords that shifted meaning on arrival. In English, "cleaning" covers everything from mopping floors to scrubbing dishes. In Japanese, <span class="jp">\u30af\u30ea\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0</span> means specifically <em>dry cleaning</em> \u2014 the professional kind, where you drop off your suit at the shop. For regular household cleaning, you\u2019d use <span class="jp">\u6383\u9664</span> <span class="gloss">(\u305d\u3046\u3058)</span> or <span class="jp">\u6d17\u6fef</span> <span class="gloss">(\u305b\u3093\u305f\u304f, laundry)</span>.</p><p><span class="jp-example">\u30af\u30ea\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\u306b\u51fa\u3059</span> <span class="gloss">(send out for dry cleaning)</span> is the standard phrase. Notice <span class="jp">\u306b\u51fa\u3059</span> \u2014 you\u2019re putting something out toward the cleaners. The shops themselves are often just labeled <span class="jp">\u30af\u30ea\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0</span> on the sign outside, no further explanation needed.</p>')

add(674, "\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9", "\u3055\u30fc\u3073\u3059", "service", ["noun", "loan word", "\u3059\u308b-noun"],
    '<p>From English "service," but it developed a meaning in Japanese that surprises English speakers: <span class="jp">\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9</span> often means something given for free, a freebie, a bonus. <span class="jp-example">\u3053\u306e\u6599\u7406\u306f\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9\u3067\u3059</span> doesn\u2019t mean "this dish is a service" \u2014 it means <span class="gloss">this dish is on the house</span>. A shop owner might throw in an extra item and call it <span class="jp">\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9</span>.</p><p>The original "service" meaning exists too: <span class="jp-example">\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9\u304c\u826f\u3044</span> <span class="gloss">(the service is good)</span>. But be ready for both. Context tells you which. If someone at a store says <span class="jp-example">\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9\u3057\u307e\u3059\u3088</span>, they\u2019re offering you a deal or a freebie, not promising attentive service. The \u3059\u308b-verb form <span class="jp">\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9\u3059\u308b</span> almost always means to give a discount or add something extra.</p>')

add(675, "\u30b0\u30eb\u30fc\u30d7", "\u3050\u308b\u30fc\u3077", "group", ["noun", "loan word"],
    '<p>Straight from English "group." The interesting thing isn\u2019t the word itself but what it reveals about how Japanese organizes people. Japanese already has several native words for groups: <span class="jp">\u7d44</span> <span class="gloss">(\u304f\u307f, a team or class group)</span>, <span class="jp">\u56e3\u4f53</span> <span class="gloss">(\u3060\u3093\u305f\u3044, an organized body)</span>, <span class="jp">\u4ef2\u9593</span> <span class="gloss">(\u306a\u304b\u307e, a circle of companions)</span>. Each carries social weight \u2014 hierarchy, formality, belonging.</p><p><span class="jp">\u30b0\u30eb\u30fc\u30d7</span> sidesteps all of that. It\u2019s neutral, modern, and flat. A study group, a pop group, a project team \u2014 <span class="jp">\u30b0\u30eb\u30fc\u30d7</span> works without implying any particular social structure. That\u2019s exactly why it got borrowed: sometimes you just need the container without the baggage.</p>')

